    id: 'w5-red-teaming',
    week: 'week5',
    title: 'Red Teaming & Adversarial Thinking',
    subtitle: 'HUHT/LULT framework, digital twins, offensive ethics, threat modelling',
    summary: 'Red teaming is role-playing as a hostile actor against your own systems to find vulnerabilities before real attackers do. Originally Cold War military concept. Key distinction from penetration testing: red teaming tests people, processes, and culture — not just technology. The HUHT/LULT framework classifies threat actors by capability and motivation.',
    examWeight: 'medium',
    mustKnow: [
      'Red teaming definition — adversarial mindset simulation, not just technical scanning',
      'HUHT/HULT/LUHT/LULT actor framework — capability × motivation matrix',
      'Digital twins for safe attack rehearsal',
      'Negative stakeholders — actors whose interests are served by the organisation\'s failure',
      'Ethics of teaching offensive techniques — dual-use knowledge problem',
      'Red teaming vs penetration testing distinction',
      'Is compliance-driven ethics sufficient for security governance?',
    ],
    definitions: [
      { term: 'Red Teaming', definition: 'The practice of role-playing as a hostile actor against your own systems, processes, or people to identify vulnerabilities before real attackers do. Scenario-driven, adversarial-mindset simulation. Tests people, processes, and culture — not just technology. Originated in Cold War military strategy.' },
      { term: 'Penetration Testing', definition: 'An authorised, scoped security test where ethical hackers attempt to find weaknesses in a system using technical tools and methods. More technical and tool-focused than red teaming. Requires written authorisation (Letter of Authorisation) to be lawful under CMA 1990.' },
      { term: 'HUHT Actor', definition: 'High Utility / High Threat. Highly capable AND highly motivated to attack you specifically. Most dangerous category. Examples: Nation-state APTs targeting critical infrastructure; organised crime targeting financial institutions. Defensive response: simulate their specific TTPs (Tactics, Techniques, Procedures).' },
      { term: 'HULT Actor', definition: 'High Utility / Low Threat. Highly capable but not currently motivated to target you. May become a threat if circumstances change. Examples: sophisticated cybercriminal groups not currently in your sector; allied intelligence services. Response: monitor for targeting shift.' },
      { term: 'LUHT Actor', definition: 'Low Utility / High Threat. Highly motivated but limited capability. Uses commodity tools or insider access. Examples: disgruntled ex-employees, low-skill hacktivists, opportunistic criminals. Response: focus on access controls and insider threat programmes.' },
      { term: 'LULT Actor', definition: 'Low Utility / Low Threat. Neither particularly capable nor specifically motivated. Examples: script kiddies, automated scanning bots, random phishing campaigns. Response: basic hygiene — patching, MFA — is sufficient.' },
      { term: 'Digital Twin', definition: 'A virtual replica of a physical or digital system used for simulation, testing, and attack rehearsal without affecting live operations. Allows red teams to test attacks against realistic models, rehearse incident response, and identify single points of failure without legal or operational risk.' },
      { term: 'Negative Stakeholder', definition: 'An actor whose interests are actively served by the organisation\'s failure. Red teaming introduces these into standard stakeholder analysis — changing security architecture decisions fundamentally. Examples: competitor seeking data leak, state actor seeking destabilisation, insider seeking financial gain.' },
      { term: 'Dual-use Knowledge Problem', definition: 'The same technical knowledge (red teaming skills, vulnerability research, exploit development) that enables legitimate security defence also enables offensive attacks. The legality and ethics depend entirely on authorisation, intent, and professional accountability context — the knowledge itself is neutral.' },
    ],
    frameworks: [
      { name: 'HUHT/LULT Threat Actor Matrix', description: 'Two axes: Capability (High/Low) and Motivation to harm this target (High/Low). Creates four quadrants: HUHT (simulate their TTPs — highest priority); HULT (monitor for targeting shift); LUHT (access controls, insider threat focus); LULT (basic hygiene sufficient). Memory: HH=Most dangerous, HL=Watch carefully, LH=Access controls, LL=Basic hygiene.' },
      { name: 'Ethical Red Team Framework', description: 'Red teaming is ethically justified when: (1) properly authorised with clear scope; (2) purpose is defensive discovery; (3) professional accountability structures are in place; (4) results inform defensive improvements. Ethical tension: teaching offensive techniques creates dual-use knowledge. Counterfactual argument: attackers learn regardless; refusing only disadvantages defenders.' },
    ],
    laws: [
      { name: 'CMA 1990 — Red Teaming Authorisation', description: 'Red teaming and penetration testing require written authorisation (Letter of Authorisation / Rules of Engagement) from the system owner. Without authorisation: S.1 unauthorised access offence. The document is not a formality — it is the legal instrument that negates the mens rea of the offence.' },
    ],
